sailpoint.integration

Class RequestResult

  • java.lang.Object
    • sailpoint.integration.RequestResult
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    IIQClient.AuthorizationService.CheckAuthorizationResult, IIQClient.IdentityService.CreateOrUpdateResult, IIQClient.PasswordService.CheckPasswordResult, ListResult, ObjectResult

    public class RequestResult
extends java.lang.Object
    A RequestResult holds information about a request on an integration system. Often requests to integrations are not executed immediately but instead launched in the background as a workflow. This can return information about the status of a request, an ID of the request, and any errors or warnings that occurred during the request. Note that request ID should be considered optional when returning a RequestResult from one of the IntegrationInterface methods since different integrations will use background requests and some won't.

    • Field Detail

      • STATUS_SUCCESS

        public static final java.lang.String STATUS_SUCCESS
        Status indicating a successful request. This has always meant what ProvisioningResult now calls "queued". The request was successfully handed off to the provisioning system but we don't know when it will be fullfilled. If the executor knows that the request will have been immediately fulfilled, as of 6.4 it should return STATUS_COMMITTED instead.
        See Also:

      • STATUS_COMMITTED

        public static final java.lang.String STATUS_COMMITTED
        Status indicating the request was sent successfully and that the provisioning system was able to immediately commit the changes. This was added in 6.4 so that older IntegrationExecutors could have a statuses that matched ProvisioningResult.
